  "local_port": 48130,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "My laptop is showing limited connectivity to WiFi while other on other laptop working properly?",
  "response": "If your laptop is showing limited connectivity to WiFi while other devices are working properly, here are some steps you can take to troubleshoot and resolve the issue:\n\n### 1. **Restart Your Devices**\n   - **Restart Your Laptop:** Sometimes a simple restart can resolve connectivity issues.\n   - **Restart Your Router:** Unplug your router for about 30 seconds, then plug it back in.\n\n### 2. **Check WiFi Network**\n   - Ensure you are connected to the correct WiFi network. Sometimes laptops mistakenly connect to a nearby network.\n\n### 3. **Forget and Reconnect**\n   - Go to your laptop's WiFi settings, forget the problematic network, and reconnect by entering the password again.\n\n### 4. **Check Airplane Mode**\n   - Make sure your laptop is not in Airplane Mode, as this will disable all wireless connections.\n\n### 5. **Run Network Troubleshooter (Windows)**\n   - Go to **Settings** > **Network & Internet** > **Status** > **Network Troubleshooter**. This will run diagnostics and may automatically resolve the issue.\n\n### 6. **Update Network Drivers**\n   - Go to **Device Manager**:\n     - Right-click on the Start button and select Device Manager.\n     - Expand the **Network adapters** section.\n     - Right-click on your WiFi adapter and select **Update driver** to ensure it\u2019s using the latest software.\n\n### 7. **Reset TCP/IP Stack**\n   - Open Command Prompt as an administrator:\n     - Type `netsh int ip reset` and press Enter.\n     - Then type `netsh winsock reset` and press Enter.\n     - Restart your laptop after executing the commands.\n\n### 8. **Check IPv4 and IPv6 Settings**\n   - Go to **Network and Sharing Center** > **Change adapter settings**.\n   - Right-click on your WiFi connection, select **Properties**, then choose **Internet Protocol Version 4 (TCP/IPv4)** and **Internet Protocol Version 6 (TCP/IPv6)**.\n   - Make sure both options are set to obtain an IP address automatically and obtain DNS server address automatically.\n\n### 9. **Disable Security Software**\n   - Temporarily disable any firewall or antivirus software to see if they are causing the connection issue.\n\n### 10. **Check for Windows Updates**\n   - Ensure your operating system is up to date, as updates can include fixes for network-related issues.\n\n### 11. **Check for MAC Address Filtering**\n   - If your router has MAC address filtering enabled, ensure that your laptop\u2019s MAC address is allowed. You can find your MAC address by typing `ipconfig /all` in the command prompt.\n\n### 12. **Check Router Settings**\n   - Log into your router\u2019s settings and ensure that there are no restrictions or settings that could be limiting your laptop\u2019s access.\n\n### 13. **Factory Reset Router**\n   - As a last resort, if nothing else works, consider factory resetting your router. Remember to back up any important settings, as this will erase all configurations.\n\nIf after trying these steps you're still having trouble, consider reaching out to your Internet Service Provider (ISP) for further assistance or checking if your laptop's WiFi hardware is functioning properly.",
